<br>
Other examples:<br>
Movies:  Because you pay to go see a movie, you are not entitled to any ownership.  You may not reproduce it in any way.  You are paying to see the movie, not to own a percentage of it.  Even if the movie sucks you are not entitled to a refund.<br>
<br>
Sports:  When you pay to go see your fave baseball team get owned by the Mets this year, you are not becoming a partial owner of the team.  You are paying to view the game.  Even if the game sucks or your team loses, you are not entitled to a refuned.<br>
<br>
MMORPG's:  You are paying to play the game.  You do not own any aspect of your character, your equipment or part of the game.  You are paying to be entertained.  You are even given a free month to determine if you will be entertained.  If you are not entertained, you can stop playing, and stop paying.  Everything that exists in the game belongs to the owner of the MMORPG.  This is evident in EQ when someone gets banned.  <br>
<br>
Thus, the company sueing here really doesn't have much of a leg to stand on.  The argument that you're paying for their time is not valid, as they could have spent that time doing something else.  Regardless of time spent, they're selling a product that is made avalible ONLY by another entity, in this case DAOC.  If DACO were to decide to shut down, you would not retain any rights to your character, equipment, etc.<br>
<br>
