href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13526>Resists</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/udeevadeelight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Deeva Deelight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orc Pawn</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/6/02 12:36:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fluclin71335flamesandrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2338.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Everlore news section</span><hr size=1> On the other hand of IP...<br>
<br>
Fair Use.  I am allowed to do with my copyright protected product certain things without fear of prosecution.  One of these things is the right of first sale of the tangible item (i.e. Book or CD).  It is because of this that a library has the right to lend books they rightfully own out to whomever they want.  They may not have the right to copy, reproduce, distribute, or create derivitive works but they surely can lend or sell their purchased copy.  This is because copyright only protects the expression of an author, not the physical tangible item.<br>
<br>
If the CD I bought at the store is a tangible item that I own, then I may sell it as I want without fear of prosecution (this is not items in the game however, it would be the CD and anything that goes along with it such as the CD key).<br>
<br>
Granted, software companies try to get around this by declaring the CD is not 'bought' but is rather licensed to use under their restrictions.  Under this theory, both you and the company are forming an agreement (contract) in which both parties are bound by the terms.  They agree to let you play the game and you agree to the laundry list of items including not to resell their product or anything within in.  <br>
<br>
So far, shrinkwrap (and clickwrap) licenses have been allowed in the courts, partially because the legislature moves too slowly to protect IP owners.  The reality is that these types of contracts may or may not be accepted in all courts due to the lack of any negotiation abilities by the parties and lack of ability to know all of the terms to the contract before you have paid the money for it (and an opened software product may only be returned for the same product...).  Contracts (which licenses are) are sometimes not binding on the parties when one is in a lesser bargaining position and may not understand the bioler plate language even if they do read it.<br>
<br>
As for the copyrightability of peoples comments on a message board, Ill save that for another rant =). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ujubershiro.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jubershiro</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dervish Cutthroat</span><br>  Posts: 164<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/6/02 12:58:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fluclin71335flamesandrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2338.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Everlore news section</span><hr size=1> Damn, Deeva got smart. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uevilnight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EvilNight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Shrieking Candyass</span><br>  Posts: 390<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/6/02 2:37:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fluclin71335flamesandrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2338.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Everlore news section</span><hr size=1> /agree Moslad 110% <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  From a legal standpoint, these people do not &quot;own&quot; these characters. Yeah, they pay a monthly fee, but that does not mean they own 1 thing in the game world. When you decide to quit EQ, you do not get to keep your character. If you stop paying, your sheet goes away into the ether after a time. Your basically paying to be entertained. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Yes, according to the law as it is now. The first thing they teach you about law is that it is always changing. I guarantee you this isn't the way it's going to be in the future.<br>
<br>
There's a massive shakedown in IP taking place... all based on a simple fact. The fact is that we posess the technology to eliminate scarcity of information. Free flow of information is taking place, and all law be damned, they aren't doing a thing to stop it... and quite frankly, with the exception of a few corporate/legal types (who represent a miniscule fraction of those involved), everyone thinks this is a good thing. We're going to have to redefine everything about copyrights, patents, ownership of information, virtual property, trade secrets... they are all based in a world where reproduction of information costs money, and the reproduction is of inferior quality to the original. In today's world, it costs nothing, other than the cost of a PC and getting online... and that's a one time fee... tiny compared to the benefits. Copies are identical to the real thing.<br>
<br>
Take a good look at what this does. If we were to ever achieve matter replication (such as seen on Star Trek) where you could just turn a shovelful of dirt into a car with a little energy, think about what that would do to basic economics in the real world. This is exactly what has happened to information... it got there ahead of the rest of things.<br>
<br>
Too bad money still talks, and bullshit still walks. <p>Raviel Darkfyre<BR>
